There is such a unique issue with Firefox's inertial scrolling on Linux that's super hard to explain.

With normal inertial scrolling you kinda "fling" the page, right? Like, a hard two finger swipe up followed by lifting your fingers off the trackpad leads the page to keep scrolling. Normally with that kind of system you can put your fingers back onto the trackpad and "catch" the page so it stops scrolling.

Firefox on Linux doesn't do that, and will only cancel the "fling" when you scroll again. So, instead of just needing to rest my fingers on the trackpad again, I need to put them on the trackpad then scroll up or down to cancel the fling. It's a really subtle issue, so I'm not exactly sure how to look it up to see if it's been reported or how to report it as an issue.

#Firefox #Linux

So Jolayemi (my Martian hacker, mixed Nigerian and German background) finds herself in a small bar on Ceres, catching a Martian bhangra-punk band called Naan Bread (it's ironic) on their new tour of the Belt.

A man comes to her attention, a Belter, who's stripping idents and credits out of people's terminals by bumping into them with a stinger panel - it uses NFC with AI to hack their terminal instantly, while the "clumsy" user apologizes for the bump.

During a big number by the band, an old favourite with a well-known dance routine, Jola intercepts the pickpocket before he would get to a friend of hers, seizing his wrist in a painful pin and dancing him out of the dance floor. She warned him that he'd been about to lift the daughter of the Loca Grigia gang's leader, and it would probably be something he could complain about briefly.

"Why briefly?"

""Cause you'll run out of air fast outside while you're complaining.

"Now, why don't you find another bar to hit up for the night, huh? As a favour to me, while I'm saving your life and all?"

He nodded shakily and moved off, pretending it was his idea to leave.

Jola turned back to the music, losing herself again in the rhythms of the band, raising a glass of fresh grade A aqua to the lead singer.

Nothing like a night on Ceres.

So back in July I had tall fescue turf laid in my back yard*. It's mostly doing great. But there's a few patches that are struggling, one or two look to be outright dead.

I'm going to oversow with seed, but I'm still trying to get to the bottom of why it's doing badly. A couple of weeks ago I fertilised the whole lawn, but that hasn't really helped.

Based on the fact that there's a couple of very small spots, like a few inches across, of dead grass, I'm starting to suspect grubs. So today I started spot-applying a pesticide / fertiliser / wetter.

But apart from that I'm not sure what to do. The only other theory I have, based on the fact that some of the poor sections coincide with where I remember the original surface being higher, is that the topsoil brought in wasn't well combined with what was already there. And the grass can't get roots in to the shitty soil under eat? Dunno. But if that's the case then I'm not sure I can do much about it until I aerate the soil and put down some top dressing. And with this grass that feels like more of an autumn job?

* Yes, grass lawns aren't the best. I need space for a child to play in, and the majority of our yard is gardens.

I think it is worth underscoring a point:

A potential conflict of interest does not mean that you are a bad person or that you made a bad decision.

It means that it is hard to _trust_ that your decisions don't have an ulterior motive because you stand to gain from some aspect of the situation.

For instance, with blocklists:

If trusted source A is acting against instance C because of behavior against an aggregating blocklist, that's a problem

1/

That's a problem because B (the aggregating blocklist) has made a choice to include A and now has a reason based on this behavior to not want to exclude A or get rid of them as a trusted source. That _incentive_ is what people mean when they talk about a conflict of interest.

It doesn't mean that the decision to act against C was wrong. It doesn't mean that they were thinking about this at all. It doesn't mean that B will actually favor them

2/

Similarly, A has another conflict of interest here if they step in to defend B: They aren't an unbiased party in this situation _either_, as the success here increases their influence.

It doesn't mean that that's why they did it, but it does mean that there is an apparent conflict of interest and people could be reasonably skeptical that the behavior doesn't have ulterior motives.

3/

The former judge in the Disney v. DeSantis federal case recused himself because a third degree relation owned a small amount of Disney stock, even though he didn't think that the case was likely to affect the stock price, the amount of stock was small, and certainly he would see no direct benefit from it.

Why? Because he was avoiding even the appearance of a COI.

He didn't say "trust me," he said "I'm going to eliminate the question."

4/

There are several ways to handle apparent conflicts of interest.

For example:

* You can _disclose_ the conflict and acknowledge it. I maintained my criticism of the #FSEP proposal here in part because it didn't disclose the relationship between the author of the proposal and TBS.

* You can have another group or entity that has a lower stake in the question make the decision or be able to overrule the decision. This is how, e.g., nonprofits work

5/

* You can recuse yourself from the decision entirely and just say "we will not make decisions/recommendations based on the behavior toward B[/A]. Others can make their own decisions here."

* You can change the dynamic to remove the appearance. For example, removing yourself from B or eliminating A from consideration in B, thus rendering them more independent.

Without taking steps here it is reasonable people could conclude that there's a COI.

6/6

>Coalition Senator and political flash-in-the-pan Jacinta Price is back at work today, and turning her attention to the real problems after spending months campaigning against an Indigenous Voice to Parliament.

>First on the agenda is why she can‚Äôt get any decent reception on her phone in Canberra.

>This comes after the Senator noticed she hadn‚Äôt received one phone call or text message from any of her coalition colleagues since the votes were counted after the Indigenous Voice referendum on Saturday night.

>While many had predicted that Jacinta Price would be ditched the moment she had expended her political usefulness, the ambitious Senator had high hopes that maybe Peter Dutton would appoint her to some sort of high-profile shadow cabinet position, like maybe the Shadow Minister for Chinese Trade Wars, or the Special Envoy to Ridiculing Trans People.

>But so far, the phone has not rung once.

>In fact, she hasn‚Äôt even received one phone call from her constituents in Central Australia, which leads her to think the Optus must be down or something.

>It would have nothing to do with the fact that the vast majority of remote Indigenous communities overwhelmingly voted yes in the referendum ‚Äì including the community where her own family is from.

>In her last media appearance of her career on Saturday night, Price has already dismissed this data as ‚Äòvoter fraud‚Äô from the corrupt Electoral Commission Volunteers in mobile booths ‚Äì as she rejected the findings that showed the yes vote in polling catchments where Indigenous Australians formed more than 50% of the population was, on average, 63% in favour of enshrining an Indigenous voice to parliament.

>But, regardless of how her own community voted, the referendum was always going to be defeated by the vast number of non-Indigenous people around the country voting no ‚Äì after months spent months telling the world that Aboriginal people didn‚Äôt want constitutional recognition.

>While the No Campaign‚Äôs Indigenous spokespeople are clearly not the sole cause of the resounding rejection of The Voice, she has most definitely become a household name off the back of it.

For the last three weeks, I've been pushing myself far too hard trying to prepare for the winter. I've been feeling awful, & frankly it was getting to be just as bad as before my cancer diagnosis & subsequent treatment. I was going to wait until next weekend to treat myself, but then I took my blood pressure last night. It was... Not good.

As a result, I forced myself to not only take a rest day, but do a little at-home phlebotomy. Unfortunately, until I have proper needles & blood bags, I have to do things the old fashioned way, which is much harder now that cooler temps are here. It's challenging for an amateur to find an artery or vein that is large enough to do the job without me bleeding to death outright. Obviously, I err on the side of caution.

The trouble with this approach is it took two hours of slow bleeding followed by almost immediate clotting & me continuously fighting to keep the wound open to accomplish my goal. Challenging to say the least, especially for someone with ADHD. Luckily, medicine is becoming a special-interest out of necessity, so I was able to keep listening to my music & focusing on the task at hand.

Without proper bags, I have no way to know how much blood I lost, but I tightened the tourniquet when I started to feel weak & sleepy. Though, some of that was likely due to not eating any solid foods prior to. I'm sure that did me no favors.

I took my blood pressure several times throughout, & this time it was back within normal range. This tells me I could have safely lost more, but after two hours, I had enough. Besides, why risk it? I'm back in a good place.

Unfortunately, the hardest part for me is closing the wound. This was only my second time using sutures. I tried a different suture this time, as the last one was so fine, I found it a bit painful at the wound site during the healing process. Today's suture was a little thicker, but also stiff as fuck & hard to work with. It kept rebounding back to the shape it was in in the package. On the plus side, the increased thickness meant I only needed four stitches instead of the six I needed last time.

Overall, I'm feeling quite a bit better. I took an aspirin with dinner to reduce the risk of throwing a clot, because at thick as my blood must have been to get my blood pressure so high, it's best to minimize risk of something preexisting breaking free & giving me a stroke or worse.

I'm glad today is over. My treatment used up nearly all of my spoons.

Starting vitals -
191/95 at 78bpm
Post-treatment
136/89 at 63bpm
Post-recovery
132/78 at 68bpm

I'm convinced I'm only alive because Robin Hobb wrote the story of my life & she's not done with me yet.

Ich nutze zur Begleitung der Gemeindelieder im Gottesdienst die verschiedensten Instrumente. Mein Hauptinstrument ist die Orgel, und dann gibt es Klavier (in der Kirche leider nur ein Tastenradio), Gitarre und Akkordeon. Funktioniert alles. Es muss zum Lied und zum Anlass passen.

Huh. Well.

One of the things I'm super insecure about as a #trans fem is my resemblance to my father. Obviously, daughters can look like their fathers, that's not remarkable, but I can't help feeling dysphoric when I look in the mirror and see that male resemblance.

Add to which the toxic masculine upbringing that my dad subjected me to, all his threats to "act like a man", backed up by violence, and this is a guy I don't want to see looking back at me.

I've sometimes wished I took after my mother more. Because much as I'm her child in the way we think, there's not much of her in my face, apart from her English complexion.

But just now I was flicking through recent photos, deciding which ones to keep or delete, when I stopped on one of them.

"Huh, that looks like Auntie D". The thought jumped unprompted into my head.

"Wait, what?"

My Dad's sister, who died when I was just a child, who I can only vaguely picture in my mind. I mostly remember her *presence*, her kindness, her intelligence, and that unapologetic femininity that awed me so much. She was a force of nature.

I... look like her? Can I trust my memory, or is it wishful thinking? Or could it be something in my eyes now that reminds me of how she looked at people?

Maybe I should just take the win. I saw, for once, the feminine genetic history of my face rather than a masculine one. Does it matter if it's my imagination or not?

Nah, I'm too damn curious. I'm going to have to look for some photos. üòÖ

Chachra structures the book as a kind of travelogue, in which she visits power plants, sewers, water treatment plants and other "charismatic megaprojects," connecting these to science, history, and her own memoir. In so doing, she doesn't merely surface the normally invisible stuff that sustains us all, but also surfaces its normally invisible *meaning*.

3/

Infrastructure isn't merely a way to deliver life's necessities - mobility, energy, sanitation, water, and so on - it's a *shared* way of delivering those necessities. It's not just that economies of scale and network effects don't merely make it more efficient and cheaper to provide these necessities to whole populations.

4/

It's also that the *lack* of these network and scale effects make it unimaginable that these necessities could be provided to all of us *without* being part of a collective, public project.

Think of the automobile versus public transit: if you want to live in a big, built up city, you *need* public transit. Once a city gets big enough, putting everyone who needs to go everywhere in a car becomes a Red Queen's Race. With that many cars on the road, you need more roads.

5/

More roads push everything farther apart. Once everything is farther apart, you need more cars.

Geometry hates cars. You can't bargain with geometry. You can't tunnel your way out of this. You can't solve it with #VTOL sky-taxis. You can't fix it with #SelfDrivingCars whose car-to-car comms let them shave down their following distances. You need buses, subways and trams. You need #transit.

6/

Even the cities we think of as motorists' paradises - such as LA - have vast, extensive transit systems. They *suck* - because they are designed for poor people - but without them, the city would go from traffic-blighted to traffic-destroyed.

7/

The dream of declaring independence from society, of going "off-grid," of rejecting any system of mutual obligation and reliance isn't merely an infantile fantasy - it also *doesn't scale*, which is ironic, given how scale-obsessed its foremost proponents are in their other passions. Replicating sanitation, water, rubbish disposal, etc to create individual systems is wildly inefficient.

8/

Creating per-person *communications* systems makes no sense - by definition, communications involves at least two people.

So infrastructure, Chachra reminds us, is a form of mutual aid. It's a gift we give to ourselves, to each other, and to the people who come after us. Any rugged individualism is but a thin raft, floating on an ocean of mutual obligation, mutual aid, care and maintenance.

9/

Infrastructure is vital and difficult. Its amortization schedule is so long that in most cases, it won't pay for itself until long after the politicians who shepherded it into being are out of office (or dead). Its duty cycle is so long that it can be easy to forget it even exists - especially since the only time most of us notice infrastructure is when it stops working.

10/

This makes infrastructure precarious even at the best of times - hard to commit to, easy to neglect. But throw in the climate emergency and it all gets pretty gnarly. Whatever operating parameters we've designed into our infra, whatever maintenance regimes we've committed to for it, it's totally inadequate. We're living through a period where abnormal is normal, where hundred year storms come every six months, where the heat and cold and wet and dry are all off the charts.

11/

It's not just that the climate emergency is straining our existing infrastructure - Chachra makes the obvious and important point that any answer to the climate emergency means building a lot of *new* infrastructure. We're going to need new systems for power, transportation, telecoms, water delivery, sanitation, health delivery, and emergency response. *Lots* of emergency response.

12/

Chachra points out here that the history of big, transformative infra projects is...complicated. Yes, Bazalgette's London sewers were a breathtaking achievement (though they could have done a better job separating sewage from storm runoff), but the money to build them, and all the other megaprojects of Victorian England, came from looting India.

13/

Chachra's family is from India, though she was raised in my hometown of Toronto, and spent a lot of her childhood traveling to see family in Bhopal, and she has a keen appreciation of the way that those old timey Victorian engineers externalized their costs on brown people half a world away.

But if we can figure out how to deliver climate-ready infra, the possibilities are wild - and beautiful.

Take energy: we've all heard that Americans use *far* more energy than most of their foreign cousins (Canadians and Norwegians are even more energy-hungry, thanks to their heating bills).

The idea of providing every person on Earth with the energy abundance of an average Canadian is a horrifying prospect - provided that your energy generation is coupled to your carbon emissions. But there are *lots* of renewable sources of energy.

15/

For every single person on Earth to enjoy the same energy diet as a Canadian, we would have to capture a whopping *four tenths of a percent* of the solar radiation that reaches the Earth. Four tenths of a percent!

Of course, making solar - and wind, tidal, and geothermal - work will require a lot of *stuff*. We'll need panels and windmills and turbines to catch the energy, batteries to store it, and wires to transmit it.

16/

The material bill for all of this is *astounding*, and if all that material is to come out of the ground, it'll mean despoiling the environments and destroying the lives of the people who live near those extraction sites. Those are, of course and inevitably, poor and/or brown people.

17/

But all those materials? They're *also* infra problems. We've spent millennia treating *energy* as *scarce*, despite the fact that fresh supplies of it arrive on Earth with every sunrise *and* every moonrise. Moreover, we've spent that same period treating *materials* as *infinite* despite the fact that we've got precisely one Earth's worth of stuff, and fresh supplies arrive sporadically, unpredictably, and in tiny quantities that usually burn up before they reach the ground.

Chachra proposes that we could - we must - treat material as scarce, and that one way to do this is to recognize that energy is *not*. We can trade energy for material, opting for more energy intensive manufacturing processes that make materials easier to recover when the good reaches its end of life. We can also opt for energy intensive material recovery processes.

19/

If we put our focus on designing objects that decompose gracefully back into the material stream, we *can* build the energy infrastructure to make energy truly abundant and truly clean.

This is a bold engineering vision, one that fuses Chachra's material science background, her work as an engineering educator, her activism as an anti-colonialist and feminist. The way she lays it out is just...breathtaking.

20/

Here, read an essay of hers that prefigures this book:

https://tinyletter.com/metafoundry/letters/metafoundry-75-resilience-abundance-decentralization

*How Infrastructure Works* is a worthy addition to the popular engineering books that have grappled with the climate emergency. The granddaddy of these is the late David MacKay's open access, brilliant, essential, *Sustainable Energy Without the Hot Air*, a book that will forever change the way you think about energy:

https://memex.craphound.com/2009/04/08/sustainable-energy-without-the-hot-air-the-freakonomics-of-conservation-climate-and-energy/

21/

The whole "Without the Hot Air" series is totally radical, brilliant, and beautiful. Start with the *Sustainable Materials* companion volume to understand why everything can be explained by studying, thinking about and changing the way we use concrete and aluminum:

https://memex.craphound.com/2011/11/17/sustainable-materials-indispensable-impartial-popular-engineering-book-on-the-future-of-our-built-and-made-world/

22/

And then get much closer to home - your kitchen, to be precise - with the *Food and Climate Change* volume:

https://pluralistic.net/2021/01/06/methane-diet/#3kg-per-day

Reading Chachra's book, I kept thinking about #SaulGriffith's amazing *Electrify*, a shovel-ready book about how we can effect the transition to a fully electrified America:

https://pluralistic.net/2021/12/09/practical-visionary/#popular-engineering

23/

Chachra's *How Infrastructure Works* makes a great companion volume to *Electrify*, a kind of inspirational march to play accompaniment on Griffith's nuts-and-bolts journey. It's a lyrical, visionary book, charting a bold course through the climate emergency, to a world of care, maintenance, comfort and abundance.

24/

The loss of American/Western monoculture, in my opinion, helped kill large-scale movements and actions in the US. There are still plenty of leftists working together to create a better world; they all watch different YouTube channels and listen to different podcasts, the creators of each forced to strive for a small portion of celebrity.

Imagine something with me.

A collective of writers, producers, and technologists. A weekly essay available in text, audio, and video form, at least two of those translated into as many languages as can be supported. This part is simple, as several already exist.

The collective is anonymous. The website is registered to a small non-profit with a handful of public board members who are paid to do the taxes and give interviews.

All media is self-hosted, and unavailable through corporate-run platforms. People find it exclusively on apps built on the @VeilidNetwork framework, to ensure the content remains available, but obfuscated. Donations can be made to the non-profit, and help fund ad campaigns everywhere else: the corporate internet, YouTube channels, any podcast willing to accept a check. All advertising the app(s), because a single outlet can be trusted to remain in the same hands, unaltered, speaking with a single (collective) voice.

Leftist history and commentary on current events, provided by persuasive writers in one anonymous voice, in one place. Calls to action that might reach enough people because they come from a single, respected source. Trust founded on the absence of celebrity and wealth‚Äîon the fact that there is nothing the collective stands to gain except a better world.

my absolute favourite artist is J.M.W. Turner. So when I saw that the Wallace Collection offered a lecture series on his art, I jumped at the chance.

I've just finished the first lecture of the series (of two) and I'm so happy. I feel so much more connected to him. And then I dove into google and found that his actual watercolour palette is on display in London. And they swatched it!

So I spoke to the folks at our registrar and based on that along with help from all you fediversians it appears that Charter is blocking bonesinjars.com via DNS.

Here's a dig trace from a helpful Charter customer:

I'm trying to contact Charter to ask them why (unsurprisingly difficult to do, especially if you're not their customer) but this begs the question: who else are they blocking and why?

I can say that this wasn't always blocked, it appears to have started a few days ago. I first suspected misconfiguration or some other mistake but now I'm curious to see if they are selectively blocking/censoring websites from their customers?

So I've been thinking about ways to investigate this. The best idea I've come up with so far is to write a script that just loops through a list of domain names attempting to resolve them with Charter's DNS servers and record which resolve with this bogus result. The main problem with this is that I can't actually query Charter's DNS servers from my network (maybe they block queries from anywhere other than their customers?).

So I'm looking for ideas. Maybe this is an honest mistake, but given the non-straight nature of bonesinjars.com and the current US political climate it's not impossible to imagine how they might be up to something other than shitty network management.

i've got a lot going for me that i feel ought to, on paper, make me desirable as a partner: i'm fairly emotionally stable / have good self-control, i'm economically stable (good job / own a house outright), i'm not bad looking & i don't have any major health problems, i'm reasonably clever, and i'm very concerned about treating people well.

however, people rarely express any interest in having me as a partner, and the few relationships i've been in have been tempestuous.

so, either:
1) i'm wrong about these metrics (ex., maybe i'm not actually as emotionally stable, clever, or ethical as i think i am),
2) they don't actually represent desirable traits,
3) i've dramatically underestimated the impact of my undesirable traits, or
4) some miscommunication is happening (ex., people get the wrong idea about me, or alternately, people are interested but only secretly)

with friendships i've mostly managed to keep things low-key enough that this isn't a problem: if somebody doesn't like me very much, they can just ghost me forever with no consequences. a romantic relationship typically involves a greater minimum level of trust so it's more complicated.

I'm hella autistic and trans (she/her). Cortex Implant makes me feel safe enough to unmask completely.

I'm an ex-hacker with a short background in computer networking (got certified in 2010 and never used it, long personal story). Went on to do freelance photography and spent the rest of my 20s working in linguistics (I briefly taught german). After seeing local language dept.s get dismantled and 2nd languages being heavily discouraged within 'murican academics (it's a huge problem, no I won't get into it), I decided to quit my passion for the next best passion: pixel art.

This account is for none of that lol I want a place to be my cyberpunk self with no expectations on the digital art I make and share. I've been doin databends ever since teen me discovered that you can hide mp3 files inside images. I use a various mix of hex editors and apps (eg. Audacity) to make my glitch art. I also do a lot of digital surrealism as well that I like to call "eye-vomit".

Everything I post on this account is copyright free btw. I deeply embody the "punk" in cyberpunk. Steal my work. Remix it. Make it yours. I just wanna add to the aesthetic of the world.

I've seen some folks confused by the mention of "the eros of the train" in that manifesto. If you weren't a teen obsessed with Atlas Shrugged, you probably wouldn't get it.

This "eros" thing isn't a lust for public transit. IMO, it's a nod to the scene where a couple of Ayn Rand's characters got real hornt after a train ride:

One of them owned the train line. The other invented the special steel from which the rails were built. Lots of folks tried to stop them, but they succeeded anyway. They boned afterward in celebration.

I mean, maybe I'm wrong, but that whole thing reads just like something 17-year-old me would have plotzed over.

That manifesto just stinks of the same actually literally horny for capitalism vibe that drips from every page of Atlas Shrugged.

Like, I don't want to kink shame, but so much of that book reads like a melange of BDSM crossed with findom.

Honestly the worst thing about being disabled is that you're so used to pushing down your needs and being told that the thing that makes you special is actually all a bunch of "negative traits and things to improve on" really hits hardest that you realise this was all targeted, when they say "lazy and unmotivated" they mean disabled people.

They mean disability. Because that was the point of these words, they were always designed to shame people who were not neurotypical. And now they are used to shame people again, but now, we do it through paperwork, hiding behind pens and suits.

When they say "you can't just expect us to change everything for you" They mean the extra requirements to level the playing field, the reasonable adjustments that look, to them, like a nice easy rest. They expect you to be un-disabled eventually, even if they say they don't, they are hoping that it will become a non-issue eventually.

"You can't just expect people to help you with all your paperwork all the time that's lazy"
No, it's my disability. Remember how people used to discriminate against people with chronic fatigue and those who use wheelchairs? They called them lazy. Yeah.

It's always that when you boil it down. And the program of "performance management" is nothing more than targeted harassment. It's a threat, designed to make you aware that you are being watched, and that you will need to put extra effort in.

Of course as a disabled person, you don't actually have any extra effort to give. You borrow it from elsewhere, you drag yourself up the stairs. People think that's time from earlier or later but it's actually "the things I wanted to do in the active hours i might get". It is the exhaustion of doing the thing my brain isn't built to do.

Dishes, maybe. Art, perhaps cleaning, you improvise and give those up, and then you regret it, it makes you feel empty, so you make sure to make time for what must be done.

You're neurodivergent so these things aren't really negotiable, to do the job, you need to be healthy, to be healthy you need to support the bits you can't ignore like that! Why work otherwise? You draw a line. "My health first"

Then they ask you to put a bit more effort in.
You're being asked to put work first ahead of everything, now also including the proof required for performance management. This work isnt getting done, of course, because youre sacrificing your health for work that you cant focus on. this is now a threat to your income- if youre not working, how will you buy food to eat?! So you just skip lunch again (haha oopsie but times are hard and EVERYONE has to try harder!) You just try hard, so hard, every day that it destroys you, and they go "oh dear irresponsible of you to be destroyed"

You're not spending more time on things because you don't have it, you have your active hours and very little else. More effort eats at your life, and performance management pushes more of your brain to how much you're being marked as "not good enough" and "must improve" and "more effort" is needed. Your mental health degrades of course, your self-confidence, as you put "more effort" into work, you put less effort into yourself. Everything starts to drop into burnout, your boss turns up the heat by ignoring the terms in your plan, the few scraps you could muster that were actual real changes that help.

Your output drops. Your mood drops. Everything drops. The performance management team gets upset because you haven't been improving, not that you haven't been trying. That needle has been in the red for months, again, like you said you wouldn't do, but they've had you on a performance plan for months now trying to avoid a discrimination suit. They claim that they want to support you, but if you need something specific? Policy doesn't support that.

So they don't support you, they don't support your needs, they allow their systems to discriminate against you through apathy, and they simply wait for the paperwork to escort you out.

If your support plan has a potential end with dismissal, it isn't a support plan. It is a way for your company to fire you for being disabled. It is a way for the company to protect itself from the idea that it didn't try.

They enshrine their failure to engage with reality in administrative nuclear glass and pass down judgment from on-high. "We would not try to hurt you" the forked tongue whips through their teeth. "We are ssssimply making sssssure that we have written down every single thing that you have done in a negative persssspective, if only you had written down all of your acheivementssssss.
You say your disability is in organisation and recall? What a Ssssssshame, what an eassssy win."

And if we get mad about it? Hmph. That's gross misconduct. Easy win.

I ain't gonna let 'em get away with it. This far, no further.

Classical logic might be a fine model of the abstract platonic ideal of what is "truth", but constructive logic certainly seems to model much better how we interact with truth on a day-to-day basis. Often we cannot decide yet whether P or not P holds, and we first need to gather more information.

I think this also applies to political issues: I often care less about the one bit of information that tells whether someone is, say, pro or anti migration, and more about the way that they got to that conclusion. In other words, I care about how they construct their evidence for or against a certain policy. Also, in many cases we do not yet have enough evidence to decide either way, but we can still discuss the shape that that evidence would take, i.e. the type of the evidence.

Anyway, if anyone would like to win my vote they now know how to do so.

‚ÄúIn order to defend the apartments in Liebig14, which were expropriated today, barricades were erected on the street. We send you a sign of liveliness.

Greetings to the squatters in Leipzig two weeks ago! Greetings to the squatters of Habersaath Street!

Instead of isolation, division, domination, exploitation and destruction, we strive for a neighborhood with exchange, solidarity, self-organization, mutual help and activity.

We are angry, we are loud. Nordkiez lives!‚Äù

Thought it was a nice touch, in an otherwise very clinical, very rushed orthopedist's mega-practice, to have the stock art in the X-ray waiting room to be of X-rayed shells. Somebody was paying attention.

Had my graduation X-ray series this morning, declaring me ready for weight bearing and no further follow ups with the surgeon.

I'm waiting for the relief to fully sink in. I've been worried about the increase in pain, and it's very good to hear that it's normal (or at least that I didn't undo the surgery somehow).

I still feel pensive though, like the world's fragility and anguish is permeating me.

What's been good lately is letting all those things be felt and known (shown) to be good. All the things I don't want to feel turn out, when experienced, to be not merely bearable but beneficial.

Even when unnameable, even when so subtle and reserved they just hold in the background, surprised to be noticed at all. Maybe they, most of all, surprise me with their goodness of being felt.

I honestly couldn't have made up a clearer example of how stochastic violence works. An angry guy listened to authoritative voices that constructed an enemy and told him that he and his community were gravely threatened. And in that conflict, he took on the role of the protagonist -- the hero who slays the enemy and saves the day. I don't care to speculate as to how he feels about this now that the deed is done, but in the moment, he probably believed he was doing something important and acting courageously.

This dynamic is why it's important to think about the narratives that reactionary leaders construct. Every time a politician or militia guy or streamer casually describes immigrants as "invaders", or trans or queer people as "groomers" who are after your kids, or uses dehumanizing language to describe moments of rebellion after police officers kill an unarmed Black person, they are constructing (or perpetuating) an enemy who is potentially an existential threat to certain people. Under those circumstances, it should surprise no one that some of those people will be moved to "defend" themselves with extreme violence.

We have lots of fictional or mythological stories available to us that illustrate "successful" resistance to external enemies who want to invade as well as internal enemies who are causing social decay or corruption. It's easy for those stories to make the leap from allegories to real life conflicts. And so anybody who is angry or fearful about changes they see (or think they see) around them can be deputized to be a Spartan from '300' or a "Wolverine" from 'Red Dawn' or that renegade cop who turns in his badge so he can *really* fight the bad guys without any red tape. There's a reason why Spartan imagery and Punisher skulls are so common on the far right. Those fantasy constructions can be really potent when people really feel threatened, and at some point, it's not just LARPing anymore.

And once they accept those roles and take real-world action, we also have lots of examples showing how they are rewarded with the hero status that traditionally accompanies those kinds of protagonists. Kyle Rittenhouse is a giant hero. Racist mass murderers are literally declared "saints". January 6 defendants are "political prisoners" who were locked up for fighting against "tyranny". On a more mundane level, all cops are self-sacrificing heroes who (say it with me!) "put their lives on the line every day" to keep us safe from "criminals", usually implying some kind of racial or ethnic group. Etc.

Maybe this all sounds really obvious. In some ways it is. But clearly we are not effectively breaking down the rhetorical frameworks that give actual, often deadly real-world violence its shape. I talk a lot about the narratives -- grounded in baseline assumptions of white supremacy, patriarchy, class hierarchy, etc. -- that inform reactionary violence, and sometimes I feel kind of silly, because "narrative" seems like such an abstract concept. But it's not. It manifests in concrete, extremely violent ways all the time.

Looking specifically at the murder and attempted murder outside Chicago, this article, written before the murder happened, offers some background into the killer's motivation. He was so fearful of a "global day of jihad" that was supposed to happen on October 13 that, even after nothing happened, his wife says he was still freaked out on October 14.

The "jihad" threat had been talked up by an assortment of reactionary leaders on both sides of the North Atlantic. Crackpot online personality Laura Loomer issued an "URGENT ISLAMIC TERROR NOTICE", warning that "HAMAS is calling on people in the 'Muslim world' to 'sacrifice themselves' this Friday", while linking to a Reuters article that says nothing about "sacrifice".

Georgia Representative Marjorie Taylor Greene responded to the idea of a "day of jihad" by saying that "I'll buy ammo while I'm home".

Turning Point leader Charlie Kirk posted on Instagram "Day of Jihad? Arm up".

Some dork with 1.1 million X/Twitter followers said he would be "carrying an extra mag".

Like any decent conspiracy theory, there was a kernel of truth somewhere at the bottom of their fears. Former Hamas leader Khaled Meshaal had issued a call for people in countries neighboring Israel to support the Palestinians in the current conflict. According to Reuters, he addressed the people of Jordan saying that "This is a moment of truth and the borders are close to you, you all know your responsibility." He also said "To all scholars who teach jihad... to all who teach and learn, this is a moment for the application (of theories)".

However people may interpret any of that, a) he's specifically addressing the current high-intensity conflict with Israel in the immediate-term, not some kind of broader ideological conflict with the West or anything so abstract, and b) he never says anything about any location other than Israel/Palestine and neighboring countries. And it mostly sounds like he's calling for protests there, as when he says "[We must] head to the squares and streets of the Arab and Islamic world on Friday".

In any event, it's a major stretch to interpret his statements as an imminent threat to people living in the US. There's just no evidence that he was calling for that. And however shitty Hamas may be, it‚Äôs questionable whether he was calling for violence of any kind in this particular instance.

But fear and anger are the grease that keeps the reactionary machinery moving. Most of the people quoted above have long track records of Islamophobic public statements (even if some of them also have long records of antisemitism). So given an opportunity to present a half-baked conspiracy theory about a worldwide threat to all that is good and decent, why wouldn't they run with it? It's exactly what they've all built their careers on. And they are not the ones who will have to deal with the violent consequences.

I know I'm very chatty today but, yikes! I was setting up a friends #Wordpress and I tried the new full site editor experience with a modern theme. And, well, that's just not how my brain works. I think in paragraphs. I'm not at all thinking about the layout *as I'm writing!* I'm thinking about the layout and menus and such *when I'm not actively writing a blog post* but the block editor, and, by extension, the full site editor, all believe you are actively thinking about the appearance and otherwise *as you are writing a 89 paragraph essay.*

You can change almost any aspect of the menus now. The width. You can put widgets where people probably think they should never go. You have far, far, more control over the *appearance* of the blog. This is fine for some people, but not for me. I think in paragraphs, not how long the widget is or similar. The Classic way of menus and widgets was limited, yes, but it got the job done for me. I didn't have to worry about height and width and similar. I'm sure that drove sighted people bananas, so I can see why sighted people like this new way of editing, but it just feels wildly bloated to me. My blog isn't actually supposed to add a new ticker or menu or banner or background widget/feature every week. People go to my stuff to *read* and not see what's shiny on my website.

Ultimately, if you want #Wordpress to become more of a flashy site designer, this new direction is perfect for you! For people that mainly write, publish, and have a bunch of stationary things on our blogs like pages, this is where the WP team just doesn't know how to make us happy so they want us to just adapt and deal with it. I'm beyond glad I use @classicpress instead!

You see, I have multiple network interfaces on my computer. Four physical ones, and a bunch of virtual ones. Some video games really don't like that and don't know how to access the internet then. A problem that the video games themselves create because they don't actually need to know that in the first place, that's the operating system's job. The latest offender on the list is Ubisoft Connect. If Ubisoft Connect is presented with my network interfaces it just craps itself and hangs in an endless loop trying to "find patches" (i.e. it's own updater breaks), which means I can't use it. Ever.

Luckily I am a Linux user. On Linux there are an abundance of sandboxing methods thanks to the server-side of things. Those you can also use on the desktop-side of things and can shove that application into its own little namespace and present it with a single network interface and suddenly everything works.

If I was for whatever reason still on Windows I'd most likely be out of luck and just couldn't play those games :blobCat_shrug:‚Äã

In theory I know there's racism, queerphobia, etc swarming around the fediverse. In practice, I don't see it due to the quality of moderation on my instance of choice.

There's still the stray hate DM, but they're always gone before I can report them. Usually because they sent from another well-moderated instance and had multiple targets, some of whom got to them first.

It's sort of an issue because I know a lot of people are in spaces where the mods and servers they federate with are unable or unwilling to do as good a job, so they get an entirely different experience.

So when I say things are great, it's true from my perspective. When they say things are terrible, it's also true from their perspective. And I can't do anything about it because it's the responsibility of the people who run their instance and links to deal with it. "Just move" is obviously untenable: they're where they are for a reason, and it's none of my business.

Best I can do is be up here in Queer Elysium and promote good vibes.

For those who do not care about privacy, security, or any other of the reasons to use self-hosted and open source platforms over corporate ones, the problem about proprietary platforms isn't that you'll have to setup a new account elsewhere when they inevitably shut down or become otherwise unusable. The problem is that all the history, all the images you sent, the posts you made, the bookmarks you have to the good posts, all of that, can be gone. In an instant.

How are you going to show off the banger that was pinned in a Discord channel when it's gone? How are you going to brag with your hundred thousand upvote post on Reddit when the platform is offline? How are you going to show me the really awesome video you made that received millions of comments and likes on YouTube when it gets removed for some reason?

We've seen how much of an issue it's been for people to find their old circles on the Fedi after birdsite died, and that's tough, but the real challenge is when the painstakingly collected custom emoji on your Discord server are gone and you remember that good one that you want to send to someone right now but you can never find it any more because it died with the platform.

What people who don't care about being the product think will be the problem is just the tip of the iceberg for them.

For others on the other hand, for marginalized groups, for people with disabilities that require extra accessibility the issue starts much earlier, that's an issue this toot doesn't even touch upon. This toot is solely about what the people who are happy with current platforms may lose in the future, even if they don't give a crap about the socio-political implications of such a platform.

I haven't been paying much attention to inflation lately, so I figured it was about time to take a look again.

YoY inflation for August and September were the same: 3.7%. This is up from July and August, at 3 and 3.2%, respectively.

Oil prices bottomed out in June, which also happened to be the peak last year, so it's interesting that inflation didn't bottom out until July. I'm guessing the effect is delayed by around a month. Which might explain why inflation didn't rise in September even though oil prices finally got back to where they had been a year before.

Trading Economics's forecast for October inflation is 3.8%, but I suspect it'll be higher due to oil prices' having recovered. They're back up to August 2022 levels. On the other hand, the velocity of money (GDP divided by the money supply, i.e. the average number of times the money supply has changed hands) is the highest it's been since 2020. So maybe they'll actually manage to bring inflation under control without inducing a massive recession after all. If so, I will still credit China's and Europe's moribund economies. Oil is not the only mechanism by which the US is able to export its inflation/import deflation.

Today is my 57th Birthday, but don't worry, I don't celebrate birthdays including my own. I don't celebrate any hallmark days, festival days, holy days or secular celebrations or commemorations. I won't ask you to donate to a cause or anything, but if you read this rant, then thank you.

I have no problem with others celebrating whatever they feel the need to. It's up to each of us to decide what is important to us as long as it doesn't hurt others.

I don't generally post my political/social opinions on here much. I prefer to post about the beauty of the world around me, my cats, and my hobby, chess. I think the world's natural beauty is worth celebrating but it is unfortunately being eroded by manmade means, and I will admit to some guilt regarding this as everyone probably should, though some are more guilty than others.

I woke up this morning to the news that a hospital had been bombed, war rages in Ukraine, fallout about the Voice Referendum still dominating the Australian news, and RWNJ's screwing up the USA, the World's most powerful country.

In the small print, a lot of species have become extinct, animal trafficking is still rife (cf Nigerian cache of pangolin skins), the World has seen record temps this year and violent hate crimes are happening across the globe.

I chose not to have children when I was younger. Growing populations, and my World dominated by the policies of Reagan and Thatcher, made me despair for the planet. When I was born the World population was under 3.5 billion, and it is now over 8 billion. Too many people clamouring for the World's precious resources, and I'm happy I didn't add to it!

It is my birthday, and I've had a pretty good life, comfortable and perhaps entitled. But being alive at this time is not something to be celebrated. We're fucking each other and the World up so tonight I'll have a drink but it will be a contemplative one rather than celebratory.

Thanks for bearing with me :)

Have been rewatching #Grimm recently to refresh my memory. It seems this horrible "We're 1/13846 German, so we named everything by German words picked randomly from a dictionary" from the writers apparently brought the CC subtitling people to their limits. The German translators certainly had a tough time but managed surprisingly well (Watched it in German the first time and had no clue how messed up the English version was back then.)

However, it's even funnier how basically every major plot point minus maybe one or so is the direct or indirect consequence of Adalind's actions in the first few seasons. This whole show is one big ripple effect Adalind keeps adding to because she doesn't really know when to quit. (Yes, she does so eventually. I suppose after 4-ish seasons the writers noticed that joke is getting old and a new villain or two might spice things up.)
